Let the cost of a duck be $d$ and the cost of a pig be $p$. We can set up a system of two equations to represent the given information. The equations are:

\begin{align*}
6d + 5p &= 213 \\
2d + 9p &= 269 \\
\end{align*}

We are trying to find the values of $d$ and $p$, so we need to solve this system of equations. We can multiply the second equation by 3 to make the coefficients of $d$ the same in both equations:

\begin{align*}
6d + 5p &= 213 \\
6d + 27p &= 777 \\
\end{align*}

Now we can subtract the first equation from the second to eliminate $d$:

\begin{align*}
(6d + 27p) - (6d + 5p) &= 777 - 213 \\
22p &= 564 \\
\end{align*}

Now we can solve for $p$:

\begin{align*}
p &= \frac{564}{22} \\
p &= 26 \\
\end{align*}

Now that we have the value of $p$, we can substitute it back into one of the original equations to solve for $d$:

\begin{align*}
6d + 5(26) &= 213 \\
6d + 130 &= 213 \\
6d &= 83 \\
d &= \frac{83}{6} \\
d &= 13.833 \\
\end{align*}

So the cost of a duck is $13.833$ dollars, and the cost of a pig is $26$ dollars.

